**Orchestrator process reminder for whoever resumes:** every task this
build went through the same pipeline — specialist implements+tests →
`tester` independently verifies (don't trust the specialist's own
COMPLETE entry) → `adversarial-generalist` reviews (required even when
tester found nothing) → orchestrator merges only once both gate entries
exist in their respective build logs → commit to git → log here. Fixes
found by either gate get sent back to the ORIGINAL specialist agent via
SendMessage (resume, don't respawn) and are re-verified with the same
revert-reproduce-restore rigor before being accepted — this caught
every real bug found this build (see logs/orchestrator.log for the
full blow-by-blow). Don't skip a step even when a task "looks simple."

**Backlog / carried-forward items (none blocking, but don't lose them):**
1. `OAuthSessionBinding` (backend/app/middleware/session.py) has no
   proactive expiry sweep, only lazy expiry-on-resolve — abandoned
   OAuth handshakes accumulate in the single always-on process. Revisit
   at Task 5A (infra) when a natural periodic-task hook exists.
2. Ephemeral `TOKEN_ENCRYPTION_KEY`/`SESSION_COOKIE_SECRET` fallback
   only logs a warning, no environment-aware fail-fast — a real
   deployment booted without these set silently loses encrypted Zotero
   tokens on restart. Revisit at Task 5A when a real deploy environment
   exists to fail-fast against (local dev already has real values set
   in `backend/.env`, so this isn't live today).
3. No unique DB constraint on `(session_id, pmid)` for `QueueDecision`
   despite SPEC §9.2 describing one row per pair. Minor, cheap, still
   open — pick up whenever touching that model next.
4. The credential-in-logs pattern (2 confirmed instances this build:
   NCBI key/email, raw Zotero tokens) has no systemic guard — Task 3D
   considered a repo-wide lint rule against logging raw request/response
   objects and deferred it as heuristic/false-positive-prone. Still
   worth revisiting with a clearer convention if a third instance shows
   up, or before Task 5B's CI is finalized.
5. The new IP-based rate-limiter key (Task 3D) has no reverse-proxy/
   `X-Forwarded-For` awareness — correct for today's direct-to-host
   local dev, but will collapse all real users into one IP bucket if a
   reverse proxy is introduced without trusted-proxy config. Must
   revisit at Task 5A if Render (or similar) sits behind a proxy.
6. No test forces `export.py`'s mid-stream logging wrapper (Task 3D
   fix) to actually fire on a real exception — coverage gap, not a
   correctness gap.

